<br>
Me, I am principially very much against death penalty.<br>
<br>
My main argument is that death is final and humans do make mistakes. Kill the wrong guy, and you can't get it undone. I think that killing is wrong, and can only be acceptable when it's utterly neccesary, like in selfdefense.<br>
<br>
The arguments for death penaly seem to be:<br>
<br>
*saving money<br>
*revenge<br>
*protection<br>
<br>
The first argument is bullshit. That it's cheaper to kill someone then to lock him up is not a valid reason to slaughter a human being!<br>
<br>
Revenge, I don't agree with that concept. Sure, I too can feel that way sometimes. Hate, selfrighteousness, jeaolusy and more are feelings that live in us all, but that does not make them right. We shoud aspire to be good, not to wallow in our lowest emotions.<br>
<br>
Protection, now that's the only argument I can feel some sympathy for. If someone have terrorized you, then he might get out one day and resume his activities if he's in jail, but if he is dead then it's over. <br>
<br>
On the whole, I think the reasons against Death Penalty far outweigh the reasons for it.<br>
<br>
By the way, things are usually more complicated then finding the right person to punish. I would reccomend the movie &quot;Dancer in the dark&quot;, where Bjork's character murder a policeman who is also one of her best friends. If one of them have to be pointed out as a villian then it's him, but he's actually not a bad person either. Hard to explain. See it. Might give you nightmares, but see it anyway. <p>Love, Edeina<br>
