</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/urolielkotn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RolielKotN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(11/26/01 4:32:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=627.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lets kill everyone who kills!</span><hr size=1> Interesting fact (these numbers aren't really completely correct, but they're close enough to imply the intended message): 75% of all prison inmates were from urban areas before they were convicted. 75% of all correctional facilities are in rural areas. When a census is taken, those inmates count as inhabitants of those rural areas, therefore inflating the population. When money is passed around, those rural areas recieve more money based on their inmate population. This means money is being taken away from the urban areas, who could use it to institute programs to lower crime and increase education. Also, since correctional facilities are usually funded with federal money, and never funded with county money, the money going to that area doesn't help the inmates either.<br>
<br>
Doesn't really have anything to do with the death penalty, but it's something else that bugs me about our penal system. <p><html><b><green>Roliel Glorysong</b></green>
